{
  "texts": [
    "Supporting this view, Arora et al. (2008) estimates that, for those inventions that are patented, patenting itself adds nearly 50% more value than if those inventions were not patented, aligning with findings from Schankerman (1998).",
    "Firms may revise their expectations about the value of a patented invention as they gather new information.",
    "To account for this, we use patent renewals as an additional signal of expected economic value (Kuhn et al., 2020; Schankerman, 1998; Pakes, 1986).",
    "The rationale is that renewing a patent-an action requiring payment of fees every four years-signals a firm's confidence that the invention will yield future economic benefits.",
    "Thus, we operationalize a firm's belief about the commercial potential of a scientific article by whether it is cited in a patent that is renewed at least once."
  ]
}